# RAG / AI Pipeline

## Three Query Surfaces

| Surface | Location | Trigger |
|---------|----------|---------|
| Web UI | `app/api/query` + `lib/query/engine.ts` | User types question in dashboard |
| Email RAG | `services/lambda-pipeline/QueryProcessor` | Inbound email question |
| FastAPI | `services/query-api/app/` | Direct API (shared with web) |

**Know which surface you're changing.** They share logic but deploy separately.

## Search Strategy: Hybrid

```
Query → [pgvector similarity] + [PostgreSQL FTS] → merge → [Cohere rerank] → top-K
```

- **pgvector:** `text-embedding-3-small` (1536 dims). Embeddings stored in DB.
- **Full-text search:** PostgreSQL `tsvector` + `tsquery`. Catches exact terms vectors miss.
- **Reranking:** Cohere (optional). Improves precision on merged results.

Don't change one leg of the hybrid without understanding impact on the other.

## Embedding Patterns

- Chunk documents before embedding (not whole documents)
- Store chunk → embedding mapping with metadata (source, page, app_id)
- Tenant-scoped: embeddings always have `app_id`. Never search across tenants.
- Idempotent: re-embedding the same chunk produces the same row (upsert by content hash)

## Prompt Engineering

- System prompts live in code (not DB) — version-controlled, reviewable
- Include source citations in answers (reference the chunks used)
- Limit context window: top-K chunks only, not entire document corpus
- Temperature 0 for factual Q&A; higher only if creativity is the goal

## Common Mistakes

- Searching without tenant filter (cross-tenant data leak via embeddings)
- Embedding entire documents instead of chunks (poor retrieval quality)
- Changing embedding model without re-embedding existing data
- Assuming web and email RAG share the same deployment (they don't)
- Not including source references in answers (users can't verify)

## WHY

RAG spans three services and two languages. A change in one surface can silently degrade another. Always identify which query path you're modifying and test it in isolation.
